
# 1. What is a Stack?

Imagine a stack of plates in a hotel.

You always **place a new plate on the top** and **remove the top plate first**.

You **cannot remove the plate from the middle or bottom**.

This is exactly how a **Stack** works.

A **Stack** is a linear data structure that follows the **LIFO (Last In, First Out)** principle.

The **last element inserted** is the **first element removed**.

Example:

```
Push 10
Push 20
Push 30

Top
 ↓
30
20
10

Pop()

Top
 ↓
20
10
```

---

# 2. Key Terms

| Term       | Meaning                                  |
| ---------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Stack      | Collection of elements following LIFO    |
| LIFO       | Last In, First Out                       |
| Push       | Insert an element onto the top           |
| Pop        | Remove the top element                   |
| Peek (Top) | View the top element without removing it |
| Empty      | Stack has no elements                    |
| Overflow   | Stack is full (array implementation)     |
| Underflow  | Trying to pop from an empty stack        |

---

# 3. Stack in Java

### Using Java Stack Class

```java
import java.util.Stack;

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
```

### Basic Operations

```java
stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);

System.out.println(stack);
```

Output

```
[10, 20, 30]
```

The **rightmost element is always the TOP.**

---

# 4. How Stack Looks

Initially

```
Empty Stack

Top
 ↓
-----
```

After Push(10)

```
Top
 ↓
10
```

After Push(20)

```
Top
 ↓
20
10
```

After Push(30)

```
Top
 ↓
30
20
10
```

After Pop()

```
Top
 ↓
20
10
```

---

# 5. Basic Operations

## a) Push (Insert)

Adds an element to the top.

```java
Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);
```

Result

```
Top
 ↓
30
20
10
```

---

## b) Pop (Remove Top)

Removes and returns the top element.

```java
System.out.println(stack.pop());
```

Output

```
30
```

Stack becomes

```
Top
 ↓
20
10
```

---

## c) Peek (Top Element)

Returns the top element without removing it.

```java
System.out.println(stack.peek());
```

Output

```
20
```

Stack remains

```
Top
 ↓
20
10
```

---

## d) Check Empty

```java
System.out.println(stack.isEmpty());
```

Output

```
false
```

---

## e) Size

```java
System.out.println(stack.size());
```

Output

```
2
```

---

# 6. Complete Example

```java
import java.util.Stack;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);

        System.out.println(stack);

        System.out.println(stack.pop());

        System.out.println(stack.peek());

        System.out.println(stack.size());

        System.out.println(stack.isEmpty());
    }
}
```

Output

```
[10, 20, 30]
30
20
2
false
```

---

